\Title {Evidence-Grounded Processing and Penetration Prediction of Mie-Scattering Spray Videos}
\Author {Linan Jiang}
\Language {en}
\Copyright {\textcopyright \ 2026. This work is licensed under a Creative Commons "Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International" (BY-NC-SA 4.0) license.}
\CopyrightURL {https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/deed.en}
\Subject {This thesis presents a computational workflow for predicting the penetration evolution of pilot diesel spray in multi-fuel marine engines and for providing geometric input to early-stage impingement-risk screening. The motivation is to support early engineering assessment of liquid diesel interaction with piston or cylinder surfaces, because such interaction may contribute to lubricant dilution, wall wetting, and poor mixture preparation. The workflow is based on room-temperature Mie-scattering spray experiments recorded in an Optical Spray Combustion Chamber with high-speed imaging. The data consist of terabyte-scale 12-bit grayscale videos collected with a fixed camera setup for one injector under multiple operating conditions and nozzle geometries. A manual calibration step first determines the spray center and the pixel-to-length scaling. The calibrated videos are then processed by a CUDA-accelerated workflow that extracts plume-resolved temporal observables and boundary evolution from the raw image sequences. To construct learning targets, penetration trajectories are represented with a reduced-order empirical fit. This step mitigates right-censoring caused by the finite observation window, improves temporal alignment across conditions, and produces representative penetration targets. On this basis, a multi-stage neural-network surrogate is developed: a deterministic baseline is trained on median penetration trajectories, a heteroscedastic model is trained on the full filtered fitted-trajectory set, and a teacher-guided refinement stage uses direct raw time-series supervision where reliable observations are available while retaining conservative teacher guidance in sparse regions. This staged design avoids the systematic underestimation bias that would arise from training a single model directly on right-censored observations with sparse or incomplete labels. The predicted mean and uncertainty can then be combined with simplified spray-angle assumptions and cylinder masks as a prototype route for probabilistic impingement screening. The main outcome is an engineering-oriented surrogate workflow that connects large-scale optical spray imaging to penetration prediction and geometric risk screening. Evaluated across approximately 15,000 penetration trajectories from 9 nozzle campaigns (roughly 400,000 labelled time steps), the refined surrogate achieves an overall RMSE of 6.9 mm (~7.2\% of the measured penetration range), with heteroscedastic prediction intervals calibrated to nominal coverage (68.5\% at 1sigma, 95.7\% at 2sigma). The method is intended as a front-end screening tool, not as a complete physical truth model of in-cylinder spray dynamics. Its current scope is limited to room-temperature non-reacting data and simplified collision geometry, but it provides a basis for later physically regularized and higher-dimensional extensions.}
\Keywords {Mie scattering\sep spray imaging\sep penetration\sep computer vision\sep surrogate modeling}
